<DOC><DOCNO> AP880502-0112 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-02-88 1335EDT</FILEID><FIRST>d a AM-BRF--CommemorativeCoins     05-02 0160</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Commemorative Coins,0163</SECOND><HEAD>Treasury Secretary Strikes 1988 Olympic Commemorative Coins</HEAD><DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III on Mondaystruck the first 1988 U.S. Olympic coins during a ceremony at theDenver Mint. The coins commemorate U.S. athletes' participation inthe 1988 Olympic Games.   Sales of the $5 gold and $1 silver coins are expected to raise$49 million, which will be sent to the U.S. Olympic Committee totrain present and future Olympians. The gold coins will sell for$35, and the silver coins for $7.   Congress has authorized the minting of a million gold coins and10 million silver coins as keepsakes of the 1988 Olympics.   Other dignitaries besides Baker present at the ceremony includedKatherine D. Orteza, the U.S. treasurer; Donna Pope, director ofthe Mint, and several past and present U.S. Olympians.   The coins will be available in mid-August at retail stores, coinand precious metals dealers and participating banks and financialinstitutions.</TEXT></DOC>